[[File:Griflet throwing Excalibur into the lake.png|thumb|Giflet throwing Excalibur into the lake in a 1470 illustration for the 13th-century French chivalric romance ''La Mort du roi Arthur'']]

'''Sir Griflet''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|r|ɪ|f|l|ᵻ|t}}, also called '''Giflet''', '''Girflet''' or  '''Jaufre''', is a [[Knight of the Round Table]] in [[Arthurian legend]]. He is called the son of Do or [[Dôn|Don]], and he is cousin to [[Sir Lucan]] and [[Bedivere|Sir Bedivere]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Monaghan|first1=Patricia|title=The Encyclopedia of Celtic Mythology and Folklore|date=2014|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438110370|page=230|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nd9R6GQBB_0C&pg=PA230|accessdate=2 November 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name="bruce">{{cite book|last1=Bruce|first1=Christopher W.|title=The Arthurian Name Dictionary|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136755385|pages=220-221|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3gaBAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA220|accessdate=2 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Like many another character in Arthurian Romance, his origins lie in [[Welsh mythology]] - in this instance in the minor deity [[Gilfaethwy|Gilfaethwy fab Dôn]], who features in [[Math fab Mathonwy]], fourth of the [[Four Branches of the Mabinogi]].<ref>Gantz, Jeffrey; trans. (1976) ''The Mabinogion''. London and New York: Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-14-044322-3}}.</ref>

[[File:Blason Girflet.svg|thumb|120px|left|[[Coat of arms]] attributed to Girflet]]

Griflet first appears as a squire and one of [[King Arthur]]'s earliest allies. When he is knighted he becomes one of the first Knights of the [[Round Table]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Story of King Arthur and His Knights|date=1909|publisher=C. Scribner's Sons|pages=45-48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s6YEAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA45|accessdate=2 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> He is one of Arthur's chief advisors throughout his career, and according to the [[Lancelot-Grail]] Cycle, he was one of the [[Battle of Camlann]]'s few survivors, and is the knight Arthur asked to return [[Excalibur]] to the [[Lady of the Lake]]. (In [[Thomas Malory]]'s ''[[Le Morte d'Arthur]]'', however, Griflet is one of the knights killed defending [[Guinevere]]'s execution when the queen is rescued by [[Lancelot]]; Malory follows the [[Stanzaic Morte Arthur|Stanzaic ''Morte Arthure'']], making Bedivere the knight who casts Excalibur into the lake.) Griflet is the hero of his own [[romance (heroic literature)|romance]], ''[[Jaufré]]'', the only surviving Arthurian romance written in [[Occitan language|Provençal]].<ref name="bruce" /> {{clear left}}

