{{about||the village in India|Tella, India|the commune in Mali|Tella, Mali|the commune in Algeria|Tella, Algeria}}
{{Unreferenced|date=September 2017}}

[[File:Mashella ena Teff.JPG|thumb|Teff and sorghum, Tella grains]]
'''''Tella''''' or '''''talla''''' ({{lang-om|farsoo}}, {{lang-ti|suwa}}, {{lang-gez|ሰዋ|translit=säwa}}) is a traditional [[beer]] from [[Ethiopia]] and [[Eritrea]]. It is brewed from various grains, typically [[teff]] and [[sorghum]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Depending on region, [[barley]], [[wheat]], or [[maize]] may be used; spices can also be added.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Dried and ground [[Rhamnus prinoides|shiny-leaf buckthorn]] leaves are used for [[Ethanol fermentation#Alcoholic beverages|fermentation]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Due to the addition of bread and use of a fermentation vessel which has been smoked over dried olive wood or [[Abyssinian rose]] wood, tella may have a smoky flavour. The alcohol content of unfiltered Tella is usually around 2–4 Volume percent, filtered tella contains about 5–6 vol%.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}

Tella is often [[Homebrewing|home-brewed]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} It may be offered in tella houses (''tellabet''), usually in regular homes, where people meet and talk to each other.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}

